Date: Fri, 30 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Viet Nam News Agency (VNA), 30 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://www.vnagency.com.vn/NewsA.asp?LANGUAGE_ID=2&CATEGORY_ID=33&NEWS_ID=111391>

Southeast Asian countries launch veterinary network
----------------------------------------------------
A veterinary network for Southeast Asia has been launched to bolster
the campaign against avian influenza, the UN Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) announced on Friday at a 3-day regional meeting of
veterinary officers and laboratory experts in Bangkok.
2 similar networks for South and East Asia will follow soon, FAO
said, stressing that it will provide around 1.2 million USD for the
creation of these subregional platforms.
The networks will bring together affected and non-affected countries
to better coordinate the control and prevention of bird flu. "Our aim
is to improve the quality of diagnosis and epidemiological data. This
will help countries to judge the effectiveness of their control
systems, identify weaknesses or share successes. Therefore, the
region will be in a much better position to respond to the avian
influenza threat," said Joseph Domenech, Chief of the FAO Animal
Health Service.
"National borders cannot stop the spread of the disease. Avian
influenza, which continues to pose a serious threat to human and
animal health requires rapid and effective national and regional
responses. While individual countries have made some progress, only
regional cooperation is likely to achieve success," he said.
Consequently, national animal disease diagnostic laboratories and
field surveillance teams will have the capacity to diagnose and
detect avian influenza. Harmonized standards on disease detection and
reporting will be applied throughout the 3 subregions.
The networks will offer training and information exchange platforms
for national laboratories and surveillance teams from 23 Asian
countries.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[An FAO/OIE Regional Workshop on Food and Feed Safety took place in
Bangkok, Thailand, from 19-22 Jul 2004, in collaboration with DLD
(Department of Livestock Development, Thailand) and JLTA (Japan
Livestock Technology Association). Additional details can be seen at
the OIE web-site, <http://oie.int/eng/press/en_040729.htm>. - Mod.AS]

