[4]
Date: 29 Jul 2004
From: Thomas M Yuill <tmyuill@facstaff.wisc.edu>

One can not help but wonder whether H5N1 has become enzootic in China
and SE Asia in "backyard" unconfined chicken flocks in rural
villages. Are such flocks, often located in remote areas, subject to
the same level of systematic prospective surveillance as are the
large commercial flocks? If there are small "wandering foci" of H5N1
circulating in unconfined poultry, control by stamping out or even by
vaccination (unless free and coupled with extensive, village-level
education) may be extremely difficult. Comments from veterinary
services officials in these countries would be very interesting.
--
Tom Yuill
University of Wisconsin
<tmyuill@facstaff.wisc.edu>
[Dr Yuill's valid comment deserves to be seriously addressed by the
relevant national and international authorities. The difficulty in
dealing with backyard and privately held avians, including
hobby-animals, has been clearly demonstrated on various occasions in
the past, recently (2003) during the HPAI outbreak in the Netherlands
and the Newcastle outbreak in California. - Mod.AS]
